48. In relationship to being a youth, E.O.R.B. asked interviewer Isobel Sheed: “Why hasn’t this example, which is a common event: A man leaves a family, starts a new life and a new family, also happened on a large scale to women? Wouldn’t that be as likely to happen to women as it was to the men?” Ann Waters: “For reasons that are mysterious to me, it doesn’t happen like that very often except if the girl grows up in a marriage where there is a lot of actual or potential violence. Divorce is a little bit like that. The state frowns on the giving or taking of slack, so a woman who won’t get a will out of her mother as long as her marriage holds together, and who resents the tyranny of having someone say all the children will be their response for you if something happens, will usually have her mother’s will as a defence against that kind of slack.” 30 49. Prior to the Women’s Movement of the early 1970’s, “Marriage was a very serious thing, a bondage”. It was “A contract from which women had to fight to extricate themselves”. 31 For many estranged New Zealand wives, independence was dependent upon releasing themselves from the emotional guilt and anguish that acted as emotional prison bars,
